1.  CPU Scheduling ke goals kya hote hain?
    5 goals: Max CPU utilization (CPU hamesha busy rahe), Max throughput (zyada processes complete hon),
    Min turnaround time (process shuru se khatam tak ka total time), Min waiting time (ready queue mein wait),
    Min response time (pehla output jaldi aaye).
    Interview Tip: MMMMM: Max util, Max throughput, Min turnaround, Min wait, Min response.

2.  Different scheduling algorithms kaunse hain?
    6 main algorithms: FCFS (First Come First Served), SJN/SJF (Shortest Job Next), Priority Scheduling, SRT (Shortest Remaining Time),
    Round Robin (RR), aur Multilevel Queue Scheduling.
    Interview Tip: Mnemonic: "Factory Schedules Production, Short Runs Round."

3.  FCFS scheduling kya hota hai?
    Pehle aaya, pehle CPU milega. Jo process ready queue mein pehle aai, usse CPU milta hai. Non-preemptive hai — 
    ek baar CPU mila toh process khud chhode ya block ho tab tak CPU uske paas rahega.
    Problem: agar lamba kaam pehle aagaya toh chhhote kaam zyada wait karenge (Convoy effect).
    Interview Tip: Drawback yaad rakho: Convoy effect = highway pe slow truck ke peeche sab stuck.

4.  Round Robin scheduling kya hota hai?
    Har process ko ek fixed time slice (quantum) milta hai. Time khatam? Process preempt ho jaata hai aur queue ke end mein chala jaata hai.
    Cyclic nature ki wajah se starvation nahi hoti. Time-slicing scheduling bhi kahte hain.
    Interview Tip: Key point: RR = FCFS + preemption. Quantum size critical hai — bahut chota toh overhead, bahut bada toh FCFS jaisa.

5.  Preemptive aur Non-preemptive scheduling mein kya fark hai?
    Preemptive mein CPU kisi bhi waqt process se liya ja sakta hai (jaise RR, Priority). Non-preemptive mein process CPU khud chhode ya
    block ho tab tak CPU rakhe (jaise FCFS, SJF). Preemptive zyada flexible hai but overhead zyada hota hai.
    Interview Tip: Easy remember: Pre = OS le sakta hai forcefully. Non-pre = process khud hi dega.

6.  Dispatcher aur Dispatch Latency kya hota hai?
    Dispatcher wo module hai jo scheduled process ko actually CPU deta hai — context switch karta hai, user mode mein jaata hai,
    correct location pe jump karta hai. Dispatch Latency = ek process stop hone se doosre process ka pehla instruction execute hone
    tak ka time.
    Interview Tip: Scheduler = decide karta hai. Dispatcher = actually karta hai.

7.  Starvation aur Aging kya hote hain OS mein?
    Starvation = ek process bahut zyada time tak CPU nahi milta kyunki high-priority processes baar baar aate rehte hain.
    Aging = solution — time ke saath process ki priority badhate rehte hain taaki wo eventually CPU paaye.
    Interview Tip: Analogy: Starvation = token number 50 wala patient wait karta hi rehta. Aging = token number ke saath urgency badhti hai.

8.  Preemptive Multitasking kya hota hai?
    OS programs ko forcefully preempt kar sakta hai — CPU le sakta hai process se bina permission ke, based on time quantum ya priority.
    Modern OS sab preemptive hain. Non-preemptive mein process khud hi CPU chhodta hai.
    Interview Tip: Modern OS = always preemptive. Windows, Linux, macOS sab preemptive multitasking use karte hain.

9.  Dispatch latency mein kya include hota hai?
    Dispatch Latency = current process ko stop karne ka time + new process ko start karne ka time. Iske andar: context switch overhead,
    mode switch (kernel to user), aur correct memory location pe jump. Real-time systems mein ye minimize karna critical hota hai.
    Interview Tip: Low latency = responsive system. Real-time OS mein dispatch latency typically nanoseconds mein hoti hai.

10.  What is preemptive multitasking?
     OS programs ki CPU time control karta hai — process ko forcefully preempt kar sakta hai predefined criteria ke basis pe
     (time quantum, priority). Programs ko cooperate nahi karna — OS automatically switch karta hai. Modern OS standard.
     Interview Tip: Windows 3.1 = cooperative. Windows 95+ = preemptive.

    

